The '''2014 Miami Beach Bowl''' was a post-season American [[college football]] [[bowl game]] played on December 22, 2014 at [[Marlins Park]] in [[Miami]], [[Florida]]. The first edition of the [[Miami Beach Bowl]], it featured the [[American Athletic Conference]] co-champion [[2014 Memphis Tigers football team|Memphis Tigers]] against the [[2014 BYU Cougars football team|BYU Cougars]]. It began at 2:00&nbsp;p.m. [[Eastern Standard Time (North America)|EST]] and aired on [[ESPN]].<ref name="faqs">{{cite web |url=http://www.miamibeachbowl.com/sports/2014/9/22/GEN_0922140857.aspx |title=FAQ |work=MiamiBeachBowl.com |publisher=[[Miami Beach Bowl]] |year=2014 |accessdate=November 15, 2014 }}</ref> It was one of the [[2014–15 NCAA football bowl games|2014–15 bowl games]] that comprised the conclusion of the [[2014 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2014 FBS football season]].
Memphis beat BYU in double overtime by a score of 55–48.<ref name="boxscore">{{cite news |title=Boxscore |url=http://espn.go.com/ncf/boxscore?gameId=400610225 |publisher=ESPN.com |date=December 22, 2014}}</ref> Afterwards, the two teams engaged in a bench-clearing brawl. <ref>Neal, David J. (December 22, 2014). [http://www.miamiherald.com/sports/college/football/article4833837.html "Memphis Beats BYU in Miami Beach Bowl; Game Ends in Brawl"], ''Miami Herald''. Retrieved December 23, 2014.</ref><ref>Associated Press (December 22, 2014). [https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaaf/2014/12/22/lynch-memphis-top-byu-55-48-in-miami-beach-bowl/20782867/ "Memphis Wins Miami Beach Bowl, then Brawls with BYU"], ''USA Today''. Retrieved December 23, 2014.</ref><ref>Newport, Kyle (December 22, 2014). [http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2308323-byu-and-memphis-fight-at-end-of-wild-miami-beach-bowl "BYU and Memphis Fight at End of Wild Miami Beach Bowl"], Bleacher Report. Retrieved December 23, 2014.</ref>
==Team selection== The game featured the [[American Athletic Conference]] co-champion [[2014 Memphis Tigers football team|Memphis Tigers]] against the [[2014 BYU Cougars football team|BYU Cougars]].
This was the first meeting between these two teams.
===BYU Cougars=== {{see also|BYU Cougars football|2014 BYU Cougars football team}} In April 2014, organizers announced that they had reached a deal with BYU to play in the inaugural Miami Beach Bowl in 2014.<ref name="scheduled">{{cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/college-football/story/_/id/10852162/byu-cougars-play-inaugural-miami-beach-bowl |title=BYU to play inaugural Miami bowl |date=April 29, 2014 |accessdate=November 15, 2014 |work=ESPN.com |publisher=ESPN }}</ref> After defeating the [[2014 UNLV Rebels football team|UNLV Rebels]] for their sixth win of the season on November 15, bowl director Carlos Padilla II extended an invitation to play in the game.<ref name="byuaccepts">{{cite web | url=http://www.miamibeachbowl.com/news/2014/11/15/Media_1115143951.aspx | title=BYU Accepts Official Invitation to Play in the Inaugural Miami Beach Bowl | publisher=Miami Beach Bowl | date=November 15, 2014 | accessdate=November 15, 2014}}</ref>
This was BYU's third Florida bowl game, following the [[1976 Tangerine Bowl]] where they lost to [[1976 Oklahoma State Cowboys football team|Oklahoma State]] 21–49, and the 1985 [[Citrus Bowl (game)|Citrus Bowl]] where they lost to [[1985 Ohio State Buckeyes football team|Ohio State]] 7–10.
===Memphis Tigers=== {{see also|Memphis Tigers football|2014 Memphis Tigers football team}} After finishing the regular season with a 9–3 record and a share of the American Athletic Conference championship, the Tigers accepted their bid to the Miami Beach Bowl.<ref name="memphisacepts">{{cite web | url=http://www.miamibeachbowl.com/news/2014/12/7/2014_Memphis_Invite.aspx | title=Conference Champs Memphis Tigers Headed to Miami Beach | publisher=Miami Beach Bowl | work=MiamiBeachBowl.com | date=December 7, 2014 | accessdate=December 7, 2014}}</ref>
This was Memphis' second Florida bowl game, following the [[2008 St. Petersburg Bowl]] (the inaugural contest for that bowl game) where [[2008 Memphis Tigers football team|they]] lost to the [[2008 South Florida Bulls football team|South Florida Bulls]] by a score of 14–41. This was the Tigers' first bowl appearance since that game. {{clear}}
