{{Infobox embryology
| Name        = Ectomesenchyme
| Latin       = ectomesenchyma; mesenchyma cristae neuralis
| Image       =
| Caption     =
| Image2      =
| Caption2    =
}}
'''Ectomesenchyme''' has properties similar to [[mesenchyme]]. The origin of the ectomesenchyme is disputed. It is either like the mesenchyme, arising from [[mesoderm|mesodermic cells]], or conversely arising from [[neural crest cells]]<ref name="pmid14699583">{{cite journal |vauthors=Weston JA, Yoshida H, Robinson V, Nishikawa S, Fraser ST, Nishikawa S |title=Neural crest and the origin of ectomesenchyme: neural fold heterogeneity suggests an alternative hypothesis |journal=Dev. Dyn. |volume=229 |issue=1 |pages=118–30 |year=2004 |pmid=14699583 |doi=10.1002/dvdy.10478}}</ref> The neural crest is a critical group of cells that form in the [[cranium|cranial]] region during early vertebrate development. Ectomesenchyme plays a critical role in the formation of the hard and soft tissues of the head and neck such as bones, muscles, teeth, and, notably, the [[branchial arches]].

